	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_35349488"><p>What wear levelling gives with one hand (performance and life) at the expense of the OS never knowing in which memory cell the data has -actually- been stored; making targeted deletion runreliable..</p><p><nobr> <wbr></nobr>..it takes back with the other; deleted files will begin to be overwritten very rapidly when new data arrives; whatever the OS thinks about it, data recovery, even using specialist tooling, will struggle to get complete files or metadata from the media if the drive has seen some real use after the data was deleted.</p><p>and, most importantly:</p><p>$ cat<nobr> <wbr></nobr>/dev/urandom &gt;&gt;<nobr> <wbr></nobr>/dev/ssdX</p><p>Just needs to be run once to -really- bollox an investigation..</p></div>
