	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_35350146"><p>Actually the man page states that on ext3 file systems running in the default manor (data=ordered) shred works fine.  If you journal data as well, not so good.</p><p>The underlying file system in use is no guarantee either.  Software, such as word processors often write out a new file each time you save, and if that is successful, they then delete the old one.  This defeats shred because shred requires a file to exist to delete it.  (It does not shred un-allocated space).</p></div>
	</div>

